         <abstract>
            <p>Let □ be a polyhedral complex embedded in the euclidean space E&lt;sup&gt;d&lt;/sup&gt; and S&lt;sup&gt;r&lt;/sup&gt; (□), r ≥ 0, denote the set of all C&lt;sup&gt;r&lt;/sup&gt;-splines on □. Then S&lt;sup&gt;r&lt;/sup&gt; (□) is an R-module where R = E[x&lt;tex-math&gt;$_1, \dots$&lt;/tex-math&gt; , x&lt;sub&gt;d&lt;/sub&gt;] is the ring of polynomials in several variables. In this paper we state and prove the existence of an algorithm to write down a free basis for the above R-module in terms of obvious linear forms defining common faces of members of □. This is done for the case when □ consists of a finite number of parallelopipeds properly joined amongst themselves along the above linear forms.</p>
          </abstract>
